**ADK Decision: Full Orchestration Skeleton (not just inference)**

ADK provides `SequentialAgent`, `ParallelAgent`, and `LoopAgent` as built-in workflow primitives, and its event-driven runtime orchestrates agents, tools, and persistent state into cohesive applications. The Hermes Loop maps onto these primitives directly — the 6 steps are not metaphors, they are ADK agent nodes. Using ADK as inference-only would waste its core value and produce a weaker architecture story for judges. Decision: ADK is the skeleton that implements the Hermes Loop as a composable multi-agent graph.

### PRD Overview for Team Alignment

---

**What we are building**

A pipeline that ingests the WEG Immanuelkirchstraße 26 dataset — 6,500 emails, 194 invoices, 135 letters, 1,619 bank transactions, plus 10 daily incremental delta packs — and compresses it into a single `building.md` per property. That file is fetched by an external AI agent via API. The agent never touches raw source data again.

---

**The three problems we solve (and how the data surfaces them)**

| Hard Problem | Where it lives in this dataset |
|---|---|
| Schema Alignment | `stammdaten.json` has canonical IDs (`EIG-007`, `EH-023`, `DL-004`). Emails name people by surname or email address. Bank transactions reference IBAN or `referenz_id`. Invoices use `INV-NNNN`. The resolver must unify all of these into one entity graph. |
| Surgical Updates | `incremental/day-01..day-10` delivers ~3 emails + 1 invoice + 1 bank tx per day. Each delta must patch only the relevant section of `building.md` — nothing else changes. |
| Signal vs. Noise | 6,500 emails contain routine acknowledgments, spam, and scheduling chatter. Only a fraction — maintenance facts, legal notices, Hausgeld disputes, Kaution records — belong in `building.md`. |

---

**System components (MVP, 48h scope)**

**1. Source Ingestion Layer**
Parsers for `.eml` (quoted-printable), invoice PDF (text extraction), German CSV (semicolon, `DD.MM.YYYY`, comma decimals), and `stammdaten.json`. Handles the format gotchas in the dataset (IBAN spacing, `bank_index.csv` vs CAMT convention difference). Feeds a normalized event stream.

**2. Schema Resolver** *(Hard Problem 1)*
Entity canonicalization engine. Input: raw string from any source (name, email, IBAN, INV-ref). Output: canonical stammdaten ID + confidence score. Uses `stammdaten.json` as the golden source. LLM-assisted fuzzy match for unstructured email bodies. Implemented as an ADK `FunctionTool` callable by any agent in the graph.

**3. Signal Filter** *(Hard Problem 3)*
Relevance scorer. Each ingested event gets a `[HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW / NOISE]` score against a category taxonomy (maintenance facts, legal obligations, financial anomalies, tenant lifecycle events). Only HIGH and MEDIUM proceed to update. NOISE is logged but discarded. Gemini-2.5-flash does the scoring pass.

**4. Surgical Update Engine** *(Hard Problem 2)*
Parses `building.md` to a Markdown AST using `marko`. Diffs the incoming fact against the current state of the target section. Applies a merge that: (a) preserves `<!-- bac:human -->` sentinel nodes — any paragraph carrying this tag is architecturally immutable, (b) injects provenance footnote `[^SRC-YYYYMMDD-ID]`, (c) updates `## Audit Trail` with timestamp and confidence. No full-file regeneration under any circumstances.

**5. Hermes Complexity Trigger**
Monitors tool-call count per ingestion task. If `>5` tool calls are required to resolve an entity or classify a document, flags the trajectory as a Learning Opportunity and runs skill extraction — distilling the resolution path into `## Procedural Memory` in `building.md`. Implemented as an ADK `LoopAgent`.

**6. building.md Output Schema**
Four canonical sections consumed by the external agent: `## Core Metadata` (property, parties, risk profile), `## Procedural Memory` (extracted skills), `## Physical State & Facts` (keybox codes, maintenance dates, utility contracts — all provenance-tagged), `## Audit Trail` (source citations, confidence scores, timestamps). Served via a FastAPI GET endpoint.

